## Diagnosis

The portaled `highlightLabelAnchor` `<div>` is `position: fixed` with no explicit `width`. A **`position: fixed` block `<div>` without `width` or `right` set expands to 100% of its containing block — the viewport** (e.g., 1440px). The CSS `transform: translate(calc(-100% − 1x), −50%)` uses percentage-based X translation, and `100%` on a fixed-block element resolves to the element's **own layout width = 100vw**, not the text width. So the translate pushes the anchor `~1448px` to the left — entirely off-screen — while the inner `motion.span` (`display: inline-block`) sits at the **left edge of the now-viewport-wide anchor**, which happens to be the notch's left edge ≈ `viewport_width − 44px`. The span appears to the right of the rail and extends past the viewport edge. Switching the anchor target from the tick button to the notch container didn't help because the anchor target only affects the `top` coordinate — the X-axis bug was entirely in the translate percentage resolution.

## Root Cause

**AP-070** (framer-motion transform clobbering a base CSS transform) was the documented anti-pattern that motivated the anchor/span split. But the split introduced a new untracked bug: `translate(-100%)` on a `position: fixed` block resolves to `-100vw`, not `-textWidth`. The fix is to abandon the `translate(-100%)` positioning model entirely and switch to `position: fixed; right: X` — where `X` is computed in JS so the anchor's **right edge** lands exactly at the inline hover-label gutter. The `%` trap disappears because `right:` never uses percentage-of-own-size math. Add `width: max-content` as a safety invariant so the div never expands beyond text width regardless of future changes.

