// Portaled label for the currently-active (or drag-targeted) notch.
// Rendered as a direct child of <body> so mix-blend-mode: difference blends
// against the page content below rather than being isolated by the rail's
// fixed-position stacking context (see AP-069, FB-155).
//
// POSITIONING MODEL (FB-156, iteration 3 → 4):
//   `right:` is set via inline style computed in JS:
//     right = viewport_width − notch.left + spacer_px
//   This places the anchor's right edge at (notch.left − spacer), which is
//   the same gutter the inline hover labels use: `right: calc(100% + 1x)`.
//
//   We do NOT use `left: notch.left + translate(-100% − spacer)` because a
//   position:fixed block <div> with no explicit width expands to 100vw.
//   translate(-100%) then resolves to -100vw (not -textWidth), pushing the
//   anchor off-screen while the inner inline-block span sits at the anchor's
//   left edge = the notch's left edge = to the right of the rail. That was
//   the visible symptom: label appeared right of the rail, past viewport edge.
//
//   `width: max-content` shrink-wraps to text as a safety invariant —
//   prevents the block from ever expanding beyond label width.
//
// MIX-BLEND-MODE: lives on this element (not the inner span) because the
//   anchor's parent is <body> = root stacking context. The span is inside
//   the anchor's own stacking context (position:fixed + transform) and
//   would isolate the blend to its empty interior. See AP-069.
.highlightLabelAnchor {
  position: fixed;
  transform: translateY(-50%);  // vertical centering only; no x-axis %
  width: max-content;           // shrink-wrap; never expand to 100vw
  color: #fff;
  mix-blend-mode: difference;
  z-index: var(--portfolio-z-scrollspy);
  pointer-events: none;
  will-change: top, right;
}
```

